blog.title: Maybe A Little Insane
blog.description:
We die containing a
richness of lovers and tribes, tastes we have swallowed, bodies we
have plunged into and swum up as if rivers, characters we have
climbed into as if trees, fears we have hidden in as if caves. Show
me a constellation composing humanity and I shall tell you its story.

summary: I don’t typically tag Taika Waititi in a post, (because I feel like that’s just inciting hate and needlessly rude) but recently...
body:
I don’t typically tag Taika Waititi in a post, (because I feel like that’s just inciting hate and needlessly rude) but recently I did and it got fans of the man attempting to attack me–

And I suddenly realized: the way they feel when we criticize TW is the same way we feel about the characters of the Thor franchise. Angry that something occurred that doesn’t apply to those characters and shouldn’t have been in the first place because–like tagging someone–it could’ve been avoided. Someone had to make a definite choice to do what happened in that film. 

So people who are fans of the film (and I’ve got nothing against being a fan! It’s fine if you wanna like the movie!) you might not understand us when we complain, but we understand you when you complain about us criticizing TW.

We know what it’s like to have a person you love be dragged through undeserving mud. Maybe the least you could do for us is to acknowledge that we have some valid issues with your favorite director and the MCU film he made.

There’s no need to fight about this. There’s no need to be verbally abusive to one another via anon messages or vicious reblogs/comments. But if we can see your side of this argument, is it really too much to ask that you see ours in return?

title: A Transformation Long in the Making - Luke Cage Season Two
body:
A Transformation Long in the Making – Luke Cage Season Two

When Luke Cage first debuted on Netflix, even a jaded media consumer could tell we were witnessing a change. For too many years media conglomerates called the shots based on faulty assumptions of what would “work” and what wouldn’t using superficial metrics and interpretations of data skewed by ignorance. Then a small but tenacious media streaming service changed the game.

At first blush, Netflix…

body:
What Lies Behind by kdm103020 and xinsomniac1101x (xCapsiclexShellheadx)

★ ★ ★ ★ ★

Words: 63,364

Pairing: Steve Rogers/Tony Stark

Completed: Yes

Four months after the Battle of New York, Steve Rogers still hasn’t managed to find his footing. The new century is strange and upsetting, and he appears to have no purpose in it. But when SHIELD sends him to liaise with the director of Stark Industries, his life starts to change in ways he could never imagine.

Or, the MCU-rooted AU, in which Steve and Tony both still maintain their secret identities.

summary: i know a part of her lives on
title: i know a part of her lives on
body:
read it on the AO3 at https://ift.tt/2uoRLDS

by Alice_not_in_Wonderland

May is dead.

It had been a car crash, they said. It was in the evening, dark enough so that a speeding driver didn’t see hers as it drove across the intersection, and she was gone only hours after arriving at the hospital with her nephew at her side. She’s gone.

But somehow, impossibly, she wakes up to a new world, with her grieving teenager trying to navigate his life and Tony Stark is…a dad?

To be fair, it’s not the weirdest thing that’s happened to her.

NOTE: Based on losingmymindtonight’s amazing work And You’ll Blow Us All Away. I can honestly say that it’s my favorite Irondad, if not my favorite fanfiction ever, out there, and Kat is the sweetest person you’ll ever meet. Please give it a read! (It’s so much better than this hot mess at least!)
